      "content": "Thanks for that. It's a good start, but my students are finding that the opposition keeps hitting them with \"human rights\" and \"moral obligation\" arguments that make the enforcement side look purely punitive or even inhumane. \n\nTo help them prepare a truly high-level rebuttal, can you expand on the philosophical or legal justifications for why national sovereignty and the rule of law should take precedence over these humanitarian concerns? I want them to be able to argue that prioritizing the state's borders isn't just a policy choice, but a fundamental moral necessity for a functioning society.",
